---
/**
 * Verifier — public-facing page that explains what a Wakir verifier
 * run produces, and renders a sample run output.
 *
 * Sibling page to `/verify/`. The two pages cover different audiences:
 *
 *   - `/verify/`   — how a third party uses `ots verify` against any
 *                    individual commit's `.ots` proof
 *   - `/verifier/` — how a third party reads the output of
 *                    `wakir verify`, the Merkle-aware archive verifier
 *                    that consumes a manifest and reports per-receipt
 *                    outcomes
 *
 * Provisional content. The `wakir verify --output json` flag is in
 * flight (manifest-v2 verifier stub). Until that lands, this page
 * renders a build-time inlined sample payload so readers can see the
 * shape of a result before they have a way to produce one of their
 * own.
 *
 * Cross-Review-Hooks:
 *   - Comms Zone-G: micro-text review pending. Marketing-text below
 *     stays factual and follows the established pattern (no hype, no
 *     marketing-pill, no "trustless" badge).
 *   - CLI-Output Schema sync with `wat-eng`: this page is a downstream
 *     consumer; any divergence between the rendered fields and the
 *     real CLI output needs a paired edit.
 */
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import VerifierResultCard from "../components/VerifierResultCard.astro";
import {
  sampleVerified,
  samplePartial,
} from "../data/wakir-verifier-result-sample";

const title = "Read a Wakir verifier result";
const description =
  "How a third party reads the output of `wakir verify`, the Merkle-aware archive verifier.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="essay">
    <header class="essay__header">
      <h1 class="essay__title">Read a Wakir verifier result</h1>
      <p class="essay__lead">
        <code>wakir verify</code> takes a manifest and an archive of
        OpenTimestamps receipts, walks every Merkle path, and reports
        per-receipt outcomes against the Bitcoin chain. This page
        explains what the output means. The result format is the same
        whether you ran the verifier yourself or you are reading a
        result someone else published.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="essay__body">
      <p>
        For verifying a single commit with the upstream
        <code>ots</code> client, see <a href="/verify/">how to verify
        a Wakir Labs commit</a>. The page you are reading now is about
        the archive-level verifier — multiple receipts, multiple
        calendars, one verdict.
      </p>

      <h2>What the verifier does</h2>

      <p>
        Three checks, in order:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          The manifest matches the archive: every hour-receipt named
          in the manifest is present, and every receipt's content hash
          matches.
        </li>
        <li>
          Every Merkle path in the manifest reduces to the
          OpenTimestamps commitment hash that was actually anchored.
        </li>
        <li>
          Every OpenTimestamps receipt resolves to a Bitcoin block
          height, via at least one calendar branch. A receipt with all
          calendar branches anchored is <em>finalised</em>; a receipt
          with at least one branch still aggregating is <em>pending</em>;
          a receipt whose Merkle path or commit-binding does not check
          out is <em>failed</em>.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        The aggregate verdict is a fold over the per-receipt outcomes.
        <code>verified</code> means every receipt is finalised;
        <code>partial</code> means at least one is still pending and
        none failed; <code>failed</code> means at least one rejected.
      </p>

      <h2>A sample result</h2>

      <p>
        The card below is the output of a verifier run against the
        TV-2 four-hour audit-trail archive. Block heights link to the
        public Bitcoin block explorer. The data is build-time inlined
        from <code>src/data/wakir-verifier-result-sample.ts</code>.
        The <code>wakir verify --output json</code> flag that will
        produce this shape directly is in flight.
      </p>

      <VerifierResultCard variant="full" result={sampleVerified} />

      <h2>What a partial result looks like</h2>

      <p>
        When at least one receipt is still pending — calendar
        aggregated but not yet anchored to a block — the verdict
        downgrades to <code>partial</code> and the affected receipt
        is shown as such. The verifier does not soften this: a
        partial result is partial.
      </p>

      <VerifierResultCard variant="full" result={samplePartial} />

      <h2>Reading the per-receipt table</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Hour-slot.</strong> UTC hour-slot identifier of the
          receipt. Wakir audit trails are aggregated per UTC hour.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Status.</strong> One of <code>finalised</code>,
          <code>pending</code>, <code>failed</code>. Status reflects
          the receipt itself, independent of the aggregate verdict.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Block height.</strong> The Bitcoin block height that
          this receipt's calendar branches resolved to. When every
          branch agrees on a single height (the common case), the
          height links to the public block explorer. When branches
          diverge, every distinct height is listed.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Branches.</strong> A summary of per-calendar
          branch outcomes, in the form <code>n/m ok</code> with
          tail counts for any pending or rejected branches.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>If the verdict is <code>failed</code></h2>

      <p>
        A failed verdict means a Merkle path did not reduce to the
        anchored commitment, or a commit-binding check rejected, or
        the manifest disagreed with the archive on a hash. None of
        these are "calendar still pending"; those are
        <code>partial</code>, not <code>failed</code>. A failed
        verdict on a real archive is a finding we want to know
        about — <a href="https://github.com/wakir-labs/site/issues">open
        an issue</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
